00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:03.680
SPEAKER: And the reason I call it
strategic practice is kind of that--

00:00:03.680 --> 00:00:06.686
they're going to be grouped by
theme, like these are problems

00:00:06.686 --> 00:00:09.060
that help me practice this
topic, these are problems that

00:00:09.060 --> 00:00:11.380
help you practice that topic and so on.

00:00:11.380 --> 00:00:15.150
But just like, you know, as I said, I'm
a chess player and my favorite chess

00:00:15.150 --> 00:00:18.250
tactics book, they'll start
out with like a chapter on pins

00:00:18.250 --> 00:00:21.240
and then chapter on forks
and chapter on skewers,

00:00:21.240 --> 00:00:24.500
or you're just practicing
individual chess tactics,

00:00:24.500 --> 00:00:26.430
and then towards the
end, you get the chapters

00:00:26.430 --> 00:00:27.720
that mix everything
together and you don't

00:00:27.720 --> 00:00:30.370
know there's going to be a
fork or a pin or a skewer.

00:00:30.370 --> 00:00:32.759
Well, you know, like on
an exam, I'm not going

00:00:32.759 --> 00:00:37.410
to tell you whether it's a fork or
a pin or a skewer, but, you know,

00:00:37.410 --> 00:00:40.560
by doing a lot of problems, you're
going to be improving your pattern

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:42.060
recognition skills.

00:00:42.060 --> 00:00:44.580
So a lot of this course is
about pattern recognition

00:00:44.580 --> 00:00:46.404
and that just takes practice, right?

00:00:46.404 --> 00:00:49.320
You have to practice as much as you
can, so the more practice problems

00:00:49.320 --> 00:00:51.127
you do, the better, right?

00:00:51.127 --> 00:00:53.460
I'm not trying to torture
anyone with a lot of problems,

00:00:53.460 --> 00:00:58.890
but as I said last time, this is a
difficult course and the best way

00:00:58.890 --> 00:01:03.120
to learn it is just by my
doing a lot of problems.

00:01:03.120 --> 00:01:04.870
So anyway, those are there.

00:01:04.870 --> 00:01:08.880
That also serves-- if you look at the
solutions to these strategic practice

00:01:08.880 --> 00:01:09.860
problems--

00:01:09.860 --> 00:01:13.560
then also, you could think of that as
kind of an example of what ideally I

00:01:13.560 --> 00:01:16.180
would like to see on the homework.

00:01:16.180 --> 00:01:18.750
So when you're writing
up your homeworks, what

00:01:18.750 --> 00:01:23.280
I don't want to see is like the kind of
thing I see sometimes, like, you know,

00:01:23.280 --> 00:01:27.870
you have like x plus 3 equals
4, and then you kind of decide

00:01:27.870 --> 00:01:30.630
to subtract 3 from both sides--

00:01:30.630 --> 00:01:35.780
minus 3 equals 1, and then I need
to square it for some reason.

00:01:35.780 --> 00:01:39.960
A 1 squared is still 1, so that's
OK, then it adds 7 equals 8.

00:01:39.960 --> 00:01:42.521
Put a box around it,
then that's the answer.

00:01:42.521 --> 00:01:43.770
That's what you should not do.

00:01:46.290 --> 00:01:51.570
What you should do is actually
have words and sentences.

00:01:54.150 --> 00:01:57.600
Just because this is a mathematical
class, doesn't mean you

00:01:57.600 --> 00:02:04.110
shouldn't be using English and
explaining things as well as equations.

00:02:04.110 --> 00:02:08.850
So I'd like you to be as clear
and detailed as possible in just

00:02:08.850 --> 00:02:10.979
fully justifying your answers, right?

00:02:10.979 --> 00:02:16.140
Like, if the answer is 42, well,
the TF knows that the answer is 42.

00:02:16.140 --> 00:02:21.240
The question is, you know, what
reasoning led you to think that?

00:02:21.240 --> 00:02:23.610
So clarity is a good word.

00:02:26.690 --> 00:02:28.170
And I'd even say honesty.

00:02:31.050 --> 00:02:36.210
I hate it when students kind of
like have a very, shall we say,

00:02:36.210 --> 00:02:39.612
sloppy argument that, I think
the answer should work out to 12,

00:02:39.612 --> 00:02:41.820
and so they're just like,
you know, put in some stuff

00:02:41.820 --> 00:02:44.700
somewhere and write it in a very
messy way and come up with 12--

00:02:44.700 --> 00:02:47.080
put a box around it.

00:02:47.080 --> 00:02:49.080
That's very bad.

00:02:49.080 --> 00:02:55.650
So if you don't understand something,
then I'd much rather that you--

00:02:55.650 --> 00:02:58.750
well of course, try to talk
to people and figure it out,

00:02:58.750 --> 00:03:02.940
but I'd rather say you don't understand
that than try to make something up

00:03:02.940 --> 00:03:06.290
like random gibberish.

00:03:06.290 --> 00:03:11.460
I always think of it as like,
you know, if I were considering

00:03:11.460 --> 00:03:17.640
hiring you to build a bridge for me,
and I'm thinking of three possibilities,

00:03:17.640 --> 00:03:18.870
like either--

00:03:18.870 --> 00:03:20.970
if you just tell me,
here's the specifications,

00:03:20.970 --> 00:03:22.740
you do this, this, and
this, I'm not going

00:03:22.740 --> 00:03:25.656
to have much confidence if you just
say that that's the answer, right?

00:03:25.656 --> 00:03:28.920
I'm not going to have blind faith
in-- even if you've successfully

00:03:28.920 --> 00:03:32.320
built bridges before, I want to
see why this is going to work.

00:03:32.320 --> 00:03:37.680
And on the other hand, if you tell
me a bridge design and it collapses,

00:03:37.680 --> 00:03:39.120
do you think I'd prefer that?

00:03:39.120 --> 00:03:42.411
Or would I prefer if you tell me, you
don't know how to build the bridge?

00:03:42.411 --> 00:03:44.910
Well, if you tell me you don't
know how to build the bridge,

00:03:44.910 --> 00:03:47.940
then I would much
rather have that happen.

00:03:47.940 --> 00:03:52.500
So clarity, honesty, and words.

00:03:52.500 --> 00:03:55.020
You may be used in other math
classes or just write, oh,

00:03:55.020 --> 00:03:57.510
the derivative of x squared
is 2x, and maybe you

00:03:57.510 --> 00:04:02.220
don't need to write any words, but
I like to see words, justifications,

00:04:02.220 --> 00:04:04.690
and thinking, not just equations.

00:04:04.690 --> 00:04:05.190
OK?

